04797nam a22006615i 9781503627901DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212021cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2020044694  a97815036279017 a10.1515/97815036279012doi  a(DE-B1597)589128  a(OCoLC)1262307401  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aRC569.5.V55 4aRC569.5.V55bR65 2021 7aSOC0510002bisacsh04a612.82231 aRollins, Oliver, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aConviction :bThe Making and Unmaking of the Violent Brain /cOliver Rollins. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface: Of the Meaning of (Scientific) Progress -- tAcknowledgments -- tPART I: THE MAKING OF THE VIOLENT BRAIN -- t1 Biology, Violence, and the Continued Debate -- t2 Finding the “Fit” -- t3 “Picturing” Risky Brains -- tPART II: THE UNMAKING OF THE VIOLENT BRAIN -- t4 Beyond Determinism? -- t5 The Taboo of Race -- t6 Fixing Violent Brains -- t7 The Limits of Scientific Conviction -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aExposing ethical dilemmas of neuroscientific research on violence, this book warns against a dystopian future in which behavior is narrowly defined in relation to our biological makeup. Biological explanations for violence have existed for centuries, as has criticism of this kind of deterministic science, haunted by a long history of horrific abuse. Yet, this program has endured because of, and not despite, its notorious legacy. Today's scientists are well beyond the nature versus nurture debate. Instead, they contend that scientific progress has led to a nature and nurture, biological and social, stance that allows it to avoid the pitfalls of the past. In Conviction Oliver Rollins cautions against this optimism, arguing that the way these categories are imagined belies a dangerous continuity between past and present. The late 1980s ushered in a wave of techno-scientific advancements in the genetic and brain sciences. Rollins focuses on an often-ignored strand of research, the neuroscience of violence, which he argues became a key player in the larger conversation about the biological origins of criminal, violent behavior. Using powerful technologies, neuroscientists have rationalized an idea of the violent brain—or a brain that bears the marks of predisposition toward "dangerousness." Drawing on extensive analysis of neurobiological research, interviews with neuroscientists, and participant observation, Rollins finds that this construct of the brain is ill-equipped to deal with the complexities and contradictions of the social world, much less the ethical implications of informing treatment based on such simplified definitions. Rollins warns of the potentially devastating effects of a science that promises to "predict" criminals before the crime is committed, in a world that already understands violence largely through a politic of inequality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aNeurosciencesxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aNeurosciencesxSocial aspects. 0aViolencexPhysiological aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Violence in Society.2bisacsh  aantisocial behavior.  abiosocial.  adeterminism.  ainequality.  anature/nature.  aneuro-prediction.  aneuroimaging.  ascientific progress.  ascientific racism.  aviolent brain.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073914540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150362790140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503627901423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/docum